07247nam a22009015i 9781782045588DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820455887 a10.1515/97817820455882doi  a(DE-B1597)674280  a(OCoLC)1419790033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aHD966b.A37 2015eb 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a333.009622300aAfrica's Land Rush :bRural Livelihoods and Agrarian Change /ced. by Ruth Hall, Ian Scoones, Dzodzi Tsikata.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2015] 1bJames Currey, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b15 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAfrican Issues ;v3600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Maps, Tables & Figures -- tNotes on Contributors -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1 Introduction The Contexts & Consequences of Africa’s Land Rush -- t2 State, Land & Agricultural Commercialisation in Kwara State, Nigeria -- t3 Recent Transnational Land Deals & the Local Agrarian Economy in Ghana -- t4 Large-Scale Land Acquisitions in Ethiopia -- t5 Land Deals & Pastoralist Livelihoods in Laikipia County, Kenya -- t6 Land Deals in the Tana Delta, Kenya -- t7 The State & Foreign in Agricultural Commercialisation -- t8 Trapped between the Farm Input Subsidy Programme & the Green Belt Initiative -- t9 Agrarian Struggles in Mozambique -- t10 South African Commercial Farmers in the Congo -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInterrogates the narratives of "land grabbing" and "agricultural investment" through detailed local studies that illuminate how these are experienced on the ground and the implications for Africa's land and agricultural economy.Africa has been at the centre of a "land grab" in recent years, with investors lured by projections of rising food prices, growing demand for "green" energy, and cheap land and water rights. But such land is often also used or claimed through custom by communities. What does this mean for Africa? In what ways are rural people's lives and livelihoods being transformed as a result? And who will control its land and agricultural futures? The case studies explore the processes through which land deals are being made; the implications for agrarian structure, rural livelihoods and food security; and the historical context of changing land uses, revealing that these land grabs may resonate with, even resurrect, forms of large-scale production associated with the colonial and early independence eras. The book depicts the striking diversity of deals and dealers: white Zimbabwean farmers in northern Nigeria,Dutch and American joint ventures in Ghana, an Indian agricultural company in Ethiopia's hinterland, European investors in Kenya's drylands and a Canadian biofuel company on its coast, South African sugar agribusiness in Tanzania's southern growth corridor, in Malawi's "Greenbelt" and in southern Mozambique, and white South African farmers venturing onto former state farms in the Congo. Ruth Hall is Associate Professor at the Institute for Poverty, Land and Agrarian Studies (PLAAS) at the University of the Western Cape, South Africa; Ian Scoones is a Professorial Fellow at the Institute of Development Studies (IDS) at the University of Sussex and Director of the ESRC STEPS Centre; Dzodzi Tsikata is Associate Professor at the Institute of Statistical, Social and Economic Research (ISSER) at the University of Ghana, Legon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLand tenurezAfrica. 0aLand use, RuralzAfrica. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAgrarian Change. 